text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!EndangeredLanguages]]%0a%0a!Jejueo %0a%0a:Author: Spencer_L%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aWe will discuss the Jejueo Language from Jeju Island of South Korea%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aJejueo is a Koreanic language spoken from the island Jeju Island in South Korea. It is often considered a dialect of the Korean language, but it is becoming recognized as a language by the South Korean government and foreign academia. Jejueo is not mutually intelligible with Standard Korean and other dialects of Korean. Due to its proximity to Japan, Jejueo also have a Japonic substratum. There was no explicit statement of the EGIDS classification of Jejueo. However, I found that the only fluent speakers of Jejueo are those residing on Jeju Island that are now over seventy years old. This would place Jejueo with the EGIDS classification of either 8a or 8b. %0a%0aJejueo was often noted to be heavily influenced by Mongol soldiers when they migrated to Jeju Island during the Mongol's rule. Due to their geographic location, there were never immediate access between mainland South Korean and Jeju Island. By the fifteenth century when the invention of Hangul permits a detailed understanding of Korean phonology, Seoul Korean and Jejueo were already divergent. By the 16th and 17th century, scholars have noted that Jejueo was already unintelligible to mainland Koreans. To further the divergence, the Korean government banned emigration of Jeju islanders to the mainland due to the fact the Jeju was used as a place of exile for disgraces scholars and officials. When these highly educated scholars got there, they started to teach children Seoul Korean and built a significant Seoul Korean superstratum in Jeju. With the ongoing wars in the 19th century, Jejueo began to be known as an incorrect dialect of Korean. Thus, the usage of the language became substantially lower.%0a%0aThere are ongoing revitalization programs for Jejueo. On Jeju Island, the local government passed an act that had ever Jeju school make Jeju language classes an extracurricular. In addition, there are many state funded and private programs that help people of all age learn Jejueo. In terms of media, Jeju Island has radio shows that exclusively uses Jejueo. Jejueo also had a inferior image to Seoul Korean, as most thought that Jejueo was impolite, uneducated, unsophisticated, and countryside-like. In recent studies, it shows that the inferior image of Jejueo is slowly decreasing and a lot of Jeju islanders are growing to be proud of their language variety. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210430-070158-462960#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Additional resources about Jejueo %0a-> - EthanW%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI found a website about Jejueo island and the language (linked below). As mentioned in the wiki article, Jejueo education in public schools is encouraged as an extracurricular activity. However, as the website points out, it is still not mandatory and the majority of teachers do not prioritize it. %0a%0aStill, there are efforts to revitalize Jejueo language. For example, many pedagogical materials and children's books in Jejueo have been developed recently. Also, Jejueo also attracts attention from academia and some linguists has published a book investigating sounds, speech system, rich inventory of suffixes, etc. in Jejueo. %0a%0aSource: https://sites.google.com/a/hawaii.edu/jejueo/; https://uhpress.hawaii.edu/title/jejueo-the-language-of-koreas-jeju-island/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210430-070158-462960#%0a#foxbegin 210503-215356-920150#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Video of Jejueo %0a-> - leah_w%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aListed below is a link to video of a man speaking Jejueo. I found it interesting reading through some of the comments. One person stated that he is Korean and can understand a little bit of what Hyun is saying, but also said the language is much different than any dialect he has heard before. Another person comments about how calm the language is. Others comment about how the language is endangered and how they want it to still be taught. %0a%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BTdYsYaoRn0  %0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210503-215356-920150#%0a#foxbegin 210509-035007-851870#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!The Ryukyuan Languages %0a-> - Russell_E%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThe situation of the Ryukyuan languages, which are a set of Japonic languages spoken on the Ryukyu Islands, is remarkably similar to that of Jejueo. Ryukyuan languages are often considered dialects of Japanese for political reasons even though they are not mutually intelligible with Japanese, or even with each other much of the time. Ryukyuan historically was viewed very negatively. Ryukyuan speakers were forced to use standard Japanese since the Ryukyu Kingdom became part of Japan. During WWII, many Ryukyuan speakers were accused of being spies and were killed. Just like with Jejueo, this negative view was reversed more recently, and there now are government revitalization efforts.%0a%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryukyuan_languages%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-035007-851870#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: D:)%0a(:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)
