diff:1620532207:1620078836:=74,84d73%0a%3c #foxbegin 210509-035007-851870#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!The Ryukyuan Languages %0a%3c -> - Russell_E%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c The situation of the Ryukyuan languages, which are a set of Japonic languages spoken on the Ryukyu Islands, is remarkably similar to that of Jejueo. Ryukyuan languages are often considered dialects of Japanese for political reasons even though they are not mutually intelligible with Japanese, or even with each other much of the time. Ryukyuan historically was viewed very negatively. Ryukyuan speakers were forced to use standard Japanese since the Ryukyu Kingdom became part of Japan. During WWII, many Ryukyuan speakers were accused of being spies and were killed. Just like with Jejueo, this negative view was reversed more recently, and there now are government revitalization efforts.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryukyuan_languages%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210509-035007-851870#%0a
